        {
          "insert": "fan",
          "attributes": {
            "code": true,
            "reference": {
              "kind": "doc",
              "path": "30-agent-layout/10-language/80-fan",
              "label": "fan — hub over children"
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "insert": ", "
        },
        {
          "insert": "arrows",
          "attributes": {
            "code": true,
            "reference": {
              "kind": "doc",
              "path": "30-agent-layout/10-language/90-arrows",
              "label": "arrows — the connection block"
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "insert": " — use these numbers. The number "
        },
        {
          "insert": "is",
          "attributes": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "insert": " the object's identity; "
        },
        {
          "insert": "text=",
          "attributes": {
            "code": true
          }
        },
        {
          "insert": " is only its short display name. Several objects may share the same text — references always go through numbers, so nothing is ambiguous. Declaring the same number twice is an error. A reference may instead be a JSON-quoted raw id ("
